Sometimes I think about all of the great playwrights and authors and what they have accomplished and how they got there and I look at my life and see that they were on a slightly more progressive track than I am.  Not that I want to be an author or a great playwright. We were talking about Beckett today in Modern Irish Drama and It dawned on me that I am a lot smarter than I give myself credit.  I don't want to sound like I am being cocky or anything, but it is true, however, i really don't apply myself.  I apply myself in my acting classes, however, I feel like it's really easy to apply myself in that because they are so instinctive.  I really don't read books as much as I should.  I don't write as much as I should. I've never explored another country. When I used to go back to Peru I would just go to the horses and kind of stay in my one little world.  I don't play music as much as I should.  I want to be multitalented. I want to be a great photographer. However, sometimes i feel like those things require more time than I have.. time that costs money that i don't.  

I really want to do what i used to do and write monologues like everyday. On my old computer I would write a journal on a Word Doc. then look at it the next day with a specific character in mind and try to make it so it would a different way.. appropriate to the character. I should do that, it was fun.  I used to be at least semi proficent in writing.  I used to love to read novels.  And I used to love failing at dance & music.  I don't know why I really don't let myself fail anymore.  

I mean I know that I am at New York University, getting pretty damn good grades and recieving a kind of respect from my teachers but there is part of me that wants it all and doesn't want to stop until she gets it, but part of me knows that it will take a little extra energy on my part to get that 'not stopping' started, and that I don't know if that will ever happen.

I'd rather say the things that I say when i am with people... and persons. i want to go some place i've never thought of going maybe that is why i am online less this year or maybe not... your amigo? marcelle

oh so i have this funny story about work: so im working at the fargo theatre the other day and this guy from, i guess he says california comes in to look at the theatre. he said he'd been there before and seemed really excited to talk about it with me... (he talked really quietly and had like white spit stick to his lips when he talked.. but i ignored it cus im nice like that) anyway... he starts talking about how movies aren't made the same as they used to be, randomly i would try to add to the conversation but he wasn't really having it so i just remined quiet and let this old guy that loved himself a lot, evidently, talk. anyway he starts listing all the movies he'd seen recently that were worthy of the 10 dollars he paid to get in. One on his list was Hotel Rwanda. He said this about the film: "Yeah. Hotel Rwanda was really good." me- "oh yeah thats what i heard, i havn't gotten to see it y--" "Yeah, being a person who has traveled to Africa a couple of times, I could really relate to that" yeah.. you guys munch on that one for awhile.
